<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-03-19T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-03-19T12:00:00-05:00" n="39" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.24/3–1148: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-03-19T12:00:00-05:00">March 19,
                                1948—noon</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>418. For Clark from Butterworth. CNO<note n="76" xml:id="d39fn76">Chief
                                of Naval Operations, Adm. Louis E. Denfeld.</note> Navy Dept states
                            no ammo in Pacific surplus essential war reserves and to draw from such
                            reserves would require action by JCS<note n="77" xml:id="d39fn77">Joint
                                Chiefs of Staff.</note> and National Security Council. CNO therefore
                            believes suggested action (Embtel 445, Mar 11) impracticable.
                            [Butterworth.]</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Thorp</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>